g bis absichtlicher Zerstörung: Gipsabgüsse in Jenaer und Wiener Antikensammlungen im 20. Jahrhundert -- tIV The Contingencies of Authenticity -- tIntroduction -- tKeep the Copy! Die Gipsabguss-Sammlung der Kunsthalle im sog. Hamburger Faksimile-Streit -- tVerkauft, verschenkt, zerstört. Vergessen? Die Frankfurter Abguss-Sammlung(en): Versuch einer Rekonstruktion -- tThe Fate of the Berlin Plaster Cast Collections: From Veneration to Destruction, Defacement, and Disposal -- tSmashing Casts: Replication of Scottish Early Medieval Sculpture as a Case Study on the Fragility of Value -- tV Revolution and Iconoclasm -- tIntroduction -- tDestruction of Plaster Casts in Workshops and Collections of Important French Institutions in the 19th and 20th Centuries -- tThe Fate of Cast Collections in French Education: Between Destruction and Abandonment -- t“A Rampage by Vandals”: The History and Destruction of the Plaster Casts of the National College of Art and Design of Ireland -- tModels for Eternity: The Changing Role of Plaster Casts at The Maryland Institute -- tVI Envois -- t‘Classical’ Plaster Casts in Enlightenment and Colonialist Discourses on Race -- tDestroy the Copy? Destroy the Copy! A History of (Non-)appreciation -- tAbout the Authors -- tIndices -- tLocations and Collections -- tIndividuals -- tGeneral0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aBased on two international conferences held at Cornell University and the Freie Universität of Berlin in 2010 and 2015, this volume is the first ever to explicitly address the destruction of plaster cast collections of ancient Mediterranean and Western sculpture. Focusing on Europe, the Americas, and Japan, art historians, archaeologists and a literary scholar discuss how different museum and academic traditions – national as well as disciplinary –, notions of value and authenticity, or colonialism impacted the fate of collections. The texts offer detailed documentation of degrees of destruction by spectacular acts of defacement, demolition, discarding, or neglect. They also shed light on the accompanying discourses regarding aesthetic ideals, political ideologies, educational and scholarly practices, or race. With destruction being understood as a critical part of reception, the histories of cast collections defy the traditional, homogenous narrative of rise and decline. Their diverse histories provide critical evidence for rethinking the use and display of plaster cast collections in the contemporary moment.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mai 2023) 4aGipsabguss. 4aIkonoklasmus. 4aPlastik. 4aSkulptur.  aCopy.  aIconoclasm.  aPlaster Casts.  aSculpture.1 aAlexandridis, Annetta, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAlexandridis, Annetta, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aAraki, Shinya, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBasile, Joseph J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBevivino, Michael Ann, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBolle-Fivaz, Clara, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFoster, Sally, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHolm, Henrik, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHume, Hannah C. M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKeller, Natalia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKellogg DiSalvo, Lauren, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLeisner, Nadine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMorinière, Soline, econtributor.4ctb4https:/